{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 05:12:19.171302", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall IP reachability across the enterprise (OSPF core/distribution/access and server farm) is healthy. DHCP and DNS are functioning; hosts can resolve and reach web services.\n- Backend web network (20.200.0.0/24) is isolated from user hosts as designed; access is only via the load balancer.\n- A performance anomaly is localized to web_server_3 (web3.local): its interface is intentionally traffic-shaped (netem + tbf), causing elevated latency and constrained throughput. This directly degrades web3.local response times and is the primary anomaly observed.\n- The load-balanced service (web99.local) is healthy and shows consistent response times; the load balancer’s backend connectivity is normal.\n\nFindings and evidence\n\nEnd-to-end reachability and routing\n- Hosts have valid DHCP leases and default gateways:\n  - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.11/24, default via 10.1.1.1 (dynamic lease).\n  - host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.20/24, default via 10.2.1.1 (dynamic lease).\n- Server access router has OSPF-learned routes to all access subnets via core (eth7), and 10.200.0.0/24 bridged locally on br0. No traffic shaping on its interfaces (tc root qdiscs are fq_codel).\n- Broad reachability tests show zero packet loss between sampled hosts and servers; RTTs generally low across the fabric.\n\nDNS and name resolution\n- curl name lookup times generally sub-200 ms from both hosts. Direct ICMP to dns_server from hosts is successful (occasional first‑probe delay consistent with ARP warm-up); name resolution is working.\n\nBackend isolation and load balancer health\n- Backend web servers are on 20.200.0.0/24 behind load_balancer:eth1. Hosts cannot reach 20.200.0.x (attempted direct pings from hosts time out), which matches the intended design.\n- Nginx config on load_balancer correctly defines upstream servers at 20.200.0.2:80, 20.200.0.3:80, 20.200.0.4:80 and listens on 0.0.0.0:80; nginx is active (running).\n- load_balancer connectivity to backends is excellent (ICMP 0.3–1.6 ms RTT to 20.200.0.2/3/4). Client access to web99.local shows consistent totals ~1.2–1.45 s from both hosts, indicating healthy load-balanced service.\n\nWeb servers (direct) performance checks\n- From host_1_1_1_1:\n  - web0.local, web1.local, web2.local total times typically ~1.05–2.1 s.\n  - web3.local total times vary, including a slow outlier ~3.87 s; starttransfer also elevated (up to ~1.56 s).\n- From host_2_1_1_1:\n  - web1.local is fastest (~1.02–1.06 s); web0.local ~1.02–2.24 s; web2.local ~1.93–2.25 s.\n  - web3.local is the slowest (~2.24–4.33 s); consistently worse than the others.\n\nICMP latency fingerprints from servers to hosts\n- web_server_0/1/2 to hosts: ~1.5–4 ms average.\n- web_server_3 to hosts: ~21–25 ms average (notably higher than peers).\n- From hosts to web_server_3, RTTs are also elevated relative to other servers in some probes.\n\nTraffic control (tc) state on routers and hosts\n- Core routers, distribution routers, server_access_router, and host interfaces show normal fq_codel root qdiscs; no artificial delay/limit detected on the forwarding path.\n- web_server_3 eth0:\n  - tc qdisc show: “qdisc netem 1: root … delay 20ms” and “qdisc tbf 10: parent 1:1 rate 1Mbit burst 500Kb”.\n  - ethtool reports 10Gb/s full-duplex link up; impairment is software-induced via tc.\n- This configuration explains:\n  - Elevated RTT (~20 ms added) in both directions for web_server_3 traffic.\n  - Constrained throughput (1 Mbit/s), increasing application response time to web3.local.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Specific and repeatable performance degradation on web_server_3 (web3.local):\n  - Elevated RTT to/from clients (~20+ ms vs ~2 ms for other web servers).\n  - Slower curl total times and TTFB versus other webX.local hosts.\n- No evidence of systemic routing or switching faults:\n  - OSPF adjacencies and routes present at server_access_router.\n  - No shaping or delay on core/distribution interfaces.\n  - Load balancer functions correctly and has low‑latency reachability to its backends.\n\nLocalization of faulty device(s)\n- Fault localized to web_server_3 (10.200.0.6) interface eth0.\n\nLikely root cause\n- Intentional/accidental traffic control misconfiguration on web_server_3:\n  - netem delay 20 ms at root qdisc.\n  - tbf rate limit 1 Mbit/s on eth0.\n- This per‑host shaping accounts for both the persistent elevated RTTs and slow web3.local responses. It does not affect the load-balanced service web99.local, which targets separate backend servers at 20.200.0.2/3/4.\n\nOverall health assessment\n- Core/distribution/access: Healthy; OSPF functioning; no loss detected; general RTTs low.\n- Server access network: Healthy; br0 bridging and routing present; no shaping.\n- DNS and DHCP: Operational.\n- Load balancer: Correctly configured and performing well.\n- Web servers: web0/1/2 normal; web3 impaired due to tc shaping on its interface.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 53330, "output_tokens": 5473, "total_tokens": 58803, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 52352}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4160}}}
